Homework 1

Question 1

Supervised learning: In supervised learning, the Y data is actually known and used for training the model. Model is given the observed output and input (from lecture slides day 1) Unsupervised learning: The response data is unknown, so the model is only given predictors and is to come up with a fit based on them

Supervised learning trains itself based on inputs and outputs while unsupervised has to determine the structure between inputs on its own.

Question 2

In a regression model, Y is quantitative (numerical values) whereas classification is qualitative (categorical values) - (lecture slides day 1). In machine learning a quantitative model will be numerically based and a classification model will have categorical labels instead.

Question 3

Regression commonly used metrics: age, height Classification commonly used metrics: color, win/ loss

Question 4

Descriptive models: Choose a model to best visually emphasize a trend in data (lecture slides day 1) Inferential models: Aim is to test theories State relationship between outcomes and predictors (lecture slides day 1) Predictive models: Aim is to predict Y with minimum reducible error Not focused on hypothesis tests (lecture slides day 1)

Question 5

Mechanistic: Parametric, uses the parametric form to predict what could be observed. Emperically-driven: Non-parametric, uses real observations to develop a theory.

Mechanistic models are typically less flexible but can that can differ based on # of parameters. Emperically driven models require a larger quantity of observations

I think empirically-driven models are easier to understand since it is coming to a theoretical conclusion based off of real world events/obersvations. It is more straight forward.

It is ideal to simultaneously achieve a low variance and low bias. A simple model which is typically mechanistic will have a high bias and low variance. An empirical model will have a high flexibility and therefore a low bias and high variance

Question 6

Given a voters profile/data, how likely is it that they will vote in favor of the candidate? This is predictive as the aim is to predict a Y (whether they will vote for a candidate) with minimum error. How would a voters likelihood of support for the candidate change if they had personal contact with the candidate? This is inferential as it is trying to establish a relationship between the outcome (likelihood of support) and predictors(contact with candidate)

Exercise 1

hwyMpg <- mpg$hwy
hist(hwyMpg)

The histogram is bimodal, with peaks its between 15-20 mpg and 25-30 mph suggesting that these ranges are the most common highway mileages.

Exercise 2

ggplot(mpg, aes(x = hwy, y = cty)) + geom_point()

The scatterplot suggests a linear relationship between cty and hwy. This means that as the city mileage increases, the highway mileage will also increase.

Exercise 3

ggplot(mpg, aes(y = reorder(manufacturer, manufacturer, function(x)-length(x)))) + geom_bar()

Dodge produced the most cars, lincoln produced the least.

Exercise 4

ggplot(mpg, aes(y = hwy, x = cyl, group = cyl)) + geom_boxplot()

As number of cylinders increases, the highway mileage tends to decrease

M <- mpg %>%
    select_if(is.numeric) %>%
    cor(.)

corrplot(M)

Number of cylinders and engine displacement are positively correlated, which makes sense because typically more cylinders = bigger engine hwy and cty mileages are also positively correlated. Both the hwy and cty have a negative correlation with the number of cylinders, implying that engines with more cylinders are less efficient. d
